WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.300


00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:01.550
DIANE DALLIS-COMENTALE: Hello.

00:00:01.550 --> 00:00:02.050
OK.

00:00:02.050 --> 00:00:03.710
Just checking.

00:00:03.710 --> 00:00:05.310
Welcome everyone.

00:00:05.310 --> 00:00:07.050
Good afternoon.

00:00:07.050 --> 00:00:11.390
I'm Diane Dallis-Comentale,
Ruth Lilly Dean of IU Libraries.

00:00:11.390 --> 00:00:13.550
Indiana University
has championed

00:00:13.550 --> 00:00:16.280
libraries and archives
of diverse collections

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:18.290
which have been
developed over centuries

00:00:18.290 --> 00:00:20.840
by expert librarians,
researchers, archivists,

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:22.070
and curators.

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:24.440
As a librarian, I
have the privilege

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:26.480
of leading one of the
top research library

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:28.680
systems in North America.

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.940
My role requires me to
simultaneously consider

00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:35.000
the past and the future, and
constantly keep those things

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.350
in the balance.

00:00:36.350 --> 00:00:39.050
I ask that we pause
for a moment to think

00:00:39.050 --> 00:00:41.300
about all that has
come before us,

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:44.660
and all those who made it
possible for us to be here,

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:46.190
together, today.

00:00:46.190 --> 00:00:49.370
Indiana University was built
on Indigenous homelands

00:00:49.370 --> 00:00:50.450
and resources.

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:52.550
With deep respect
and appreciation,

00:00:52.550 --> 00:00:56.340
I acknowledge the Indigenous
nations' communities, families,

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:00.780
and especially those of the
Miami, Delaware, Potawatomi,

00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:02.340
and Shawnee people.

00:01:02.340 --> 00:01:04.830
The Foundation of our
state and our University

00:01:04.830 --> 00:01:08.280
was built on unceded land
by indentured laborers,

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:11.670
immigrants, and many people
who endured and struggled

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:14.820
those whose names
and lives have often

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:17.160
been forgotten by history.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:20.640
With this in mind, before
our program starts,

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:23.400
I hope that you consider the
opportunity and privilege we

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:26.050
all share in being here today.

00:01:26.050 --> 00:01:28.770
All who have come
before us, all who

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:32.160
have made it possible
to be here today,

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:36.600
open to a conversation
across many generations

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:39.430
and with many new
ideas coming together.

00:01:39.430 --> 00:01:41.790
This is a privilege
we share, and I really

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:43.920
appreciate your thoughts
about that as you go

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:45.850
through the rest of your day.

00:01:45.850 --> 00:01:49.020
So on behalf of
our partners, I am

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:52.950
thrilled by your interest in
the significance of archives

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:54.840
and the role of the
national government.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:58.500
It is an honor for IU to host
this discussion as we kick off

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:01.710
American Archives Month
as well as a month

00:02:01.710 --> 00:02:04.150
celebrating archives of
the state of Indiana.

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:07.770
Thanks to a formal
proclamation by our governor.

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:10.979
Our partners for this gathering
are listed on the screen above.

00:02:10.979 --> 00:02:12.840
Though, I am specifically
calling attention

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:14.490
to our friends at
the Luddy School

00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:17.310
of Informatics Department
of Information and Library

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:20.220
Science, the Hamilton
Lugar School of Global

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:23.250
and International Studies,
and the Paul O'Neill

00:02:23.250 --> 00:02:26.040
School of Public and
Environmental Affairs.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:30.345
If you are here as part of
the fall 2023 Themester, Lux

00:02:30.345 --> 00:02:33.390
et Veritas, you deserve
a special welcome.

00:02:33.390 --> 00:02:35.790
Thank you to the College
of Arts and Sciences

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:37.920
for more than a
decade of engaged

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:41.460
learning through the exceptional
issues based Themester

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:43.620
teaching and programming.

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:47.790
It turns out that this
year's Themester theme, light

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:50.400
and truth, was quite
inspirational to my colleague

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.830
Dina Kellams, Director
of University Archives,

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:56.190
and the incredible team
of archivists she leads.

00:02:56.190 --> 00:02:58.530
When they first began
discussing and planning

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:06.350
this year's activities,
they knew right away

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:09.470
that the person they
wanted to have come,

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:11.630
who could best
illustrate and illuminate

00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:16.190
how important archives are,
is our former Archivist

00:03:16.190 --> 00:03:18.710
of the United States,
David Ferriero.

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:20.810
In a moment I will
hand over the stage

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:22.970
to Sara Stefani one
of the IU Library's

00:03:22.970 --> 00:03:25.640
many outstanding archivists,
who will be moderating

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.320
this discussion today.

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:28.880
Sara is the modical--

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:30.860
political-- modern--
I'm so sorry.

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:33.560
Modern Political Papers
Archivist and she

00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:36.050
joined the IU Libraries
in 2018 to work

00:03:36.050 --> 00:03:40.460
on the papers of the longtime
Indiana Senator, Richard Lugar.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:43.670
Sara received her doctorate
from Yale University

00:03:43.670 --> 00:03:46.790
in Slavic languages
and literature.

00:03:46.790 --> 00:03:50.450
She oversees our collections
of papers from Congresswoman,

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:54.290
Jill Long Thompson, Senator
Birch Bayh, and Congressman Lee

00:03:54.290 --> 00:03:56.390
Hamilton, among many others.

00:03:56.390 --> 00:03:59.360
She is a member of the steering
committee of the Congressional

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:03.480
Papers Section of the
American Society of Archivist,

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:06.600
and the president of the
Association of Centers

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:08.460
for the Study of Congress.

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:11.400
Sarah will be leading the
question and answer session

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.670
with our distinguished
guest, David Ferriero, who

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:17.160
served as the 10th archivist
of the United States

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:20.880
from 2009 through April 2022.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:24.330
President Barack Obama
nominated Mr Ferriero,

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:26.370
who was confirmed
by the US Senate

00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:29.130
and sworn in November of 2020--

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:30.870
sorry, 2009.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:34.230
As archivist, Mr Ferriero
oversaw the addition

00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:37.170
of three new
presidential libraries

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:41.940
to the National Archives
and Records Administration

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:45.090
Presidential Library systems.

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:47.010
Before leading the
National Archives,

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:50.580
Mr Ferriero served as
Andrew W. Mellon, director

00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:52.200
of New York Public Library.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.970
He was part of the
leadership team

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:58.050
responsible for integrating the
four research libraries and 87

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:01.390
branches to create the
largest public library

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:04.540
system in the United States
and one of the largest research

00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:06.100
libraries in the world.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:10.330
Mr Ferriero served in
top leadership positions

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:13.390
in two of the nation's
highly ranked universities,

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:16.190
the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology in Cambridge,

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:20.200
Massachusetts, and Duke
University in Durham, North

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:21.070
Carolina.

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:25.570
Mr Ferriero earned bachelor's
degrees and master's degrees

00:05:25.570 --> 00:05:28.420
in English Literature from
Northeastern University

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:32.080
in Boston and a master's degree
from Simmons College of Library

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:34.510
and Information
Science in Boston.

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:38.050
Mr Ferriero also served as
a Navy hospital corpsman

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:39.580
during the Vietnam War.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:43.660
Before we jump into
the Q&A our moderator,

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:46.840
Sara Stefani has a
few details regarding

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:48.470
audience participation.

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:50.290
And I'm going to
hand things over

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:52.360
to Sarah's very capable hands.

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:54.250
And I sincerely
appreciate all of you

00:05:54.250 --> 00:05:55.450
being in attendance today.

00:05:55.450 --> 00:05:56.670
Thank you.

