00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:11.690
Actually, my first
question is unplanned

00:08:11.690 --> 00:08:13.250
because it's
something that I just

00:08:13.250 --> 00:08:19.400
learned right at the beginning
of this event, which is--

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:20.790
David, would you
like to tell us.

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:23.780
So as soon as you
came into the room,

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:25.910
you recognized these murals.

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:30.050
And you asked, are these
Thomas Hart Benton?

00:08:30.050 --> 00:08:31.250
And why did you ask that?

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:33.870
What prompted you?

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:36.770
DAVID FERRIERO: Because
I recognized his style.

00:08:36.770 --> 00:08:41.929
And a wonderful story about
Harry S. Truman Presidential

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:47.120
Library, where we have
a Thomas Hart Benton.

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:51.740
And Benton painted it while
Harry was still alive.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:53.750
And we have
wonderful photographs

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:59.840
in the Library of Benton
on a ladder painting

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:03.920
next to Harry Truman on the
ladder painting a cloud.

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:05.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:09.470
And we also have wonderful
photographs of Benton,

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:13.130
after Harry left, painting
over what Harry did.

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:16.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:19.817
SARA STEFANI: So
essentially erasing history.

00:09:19.817 --> 00:09:21.150
DAVID FERRIERO: It's underneath.

00:09:21.150 --> 00:09:22.170
It's underneath.

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:24.810
It's still there.

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:27.450
SARA STEFANI: So my first
question, essentially,

00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:30.640
was to ask you about being
the archivist of the United

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:33.600
States, which later
I'm going to follow up

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:37.200
to ask you to explain to the
audience what a Presidential

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:38.070
Library is.

00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:43.320
But first let me ask you--
just for our general crowd--

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:45.540
can you explain a
little bit of what

00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:49.507
does it mean to be the
archivist of the United States?

00:09:49.507 --> 00:09:51.840
DAVID FERRIERO: A lot of
things that they didn't tell me

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:53.137
during the interview process.

00:09:53.137 --> 00:09:53.970
SARA STEFANI: Right.

00:09:53.970 --> 00:09:55.443
Or in library
school, I'm assuming.

00:09:55.443 --> 00:09:56.610
DAVID FERRIERO: Forget that.

00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:56.970
SARA STEFANI: Yeah, forget that.

00:09:56.970 --> 00:09:57.360
[LAUGHS]

00:09:57.360 --> 00:09:58.235
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah.

00:09:58.235 --> 00:09:58.740
Right.

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:01.440
The Archivist of
the United States

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:07.110
is responsible for overseeing
the creation, management,

00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:12.180
and access to the
records created

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:13.380
by the federal government.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:14.490
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:18.460
DAVID FERRIERO: To follow a
prescribed set of laws, Federal

00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:20.050
Records Act,
Presidential Records

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:22.390
Act, that kind of lay
down the law about how

00:10:22.390 --> 00:10:24.280
things should work.

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:36.220
And provide access to the papers
of the government in order

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:38.560
for the American people
to hold their government

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:42.130
accountable for its actions
and to learn from our past.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:43.210
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:10:43.210 --> 00:10:45.978
So how does one become the
Archivist of the United States.

00:10:45.978 --> 00:10:48.520
DAVID FERRIERO: Well there was
this ad in the New York Times.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:48.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.100
SARA STEFANI: I was going
to say, I'm an archivist

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:53.860
and I want to be the Archivist
of the United States someday.

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:55.240
So.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:57.310
Yeah, do I check Indeed or?

00:10:57.310 --> 00:10:58.810
DAVID FERRIERO: It
was very strange.

00:10:58.810 --> 00:11:02.710
I was at the New
York Public Library

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:08.470
and what looks like a very
cushy job from this perspective.

00:11:08.470 --> 00:11:11.050
I had a wonderful
office on Fifth Avenue

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:12.900
with a lion outside my window.

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:14.200
SARA STEFANI: Ooh.

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:19.140
DAVID FERRIERO: And a Friday
afternoon in April of whatever,

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:21.240
2009.

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:23.070
My assistant came in
and said the White

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:24.420
House is on the phone.

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:25.672
So I got on the phone.

00:11:25.672 --> 00:11:26.880
SARA STEFANI: Was it April 1?

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:27.570
DAVID FERRIERO: No, it wasn't.

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:28.620
[SUBDUED LAUGHTER]

00:11:28.620 --> 00:11:31.590
It was around Patriots Day.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.720
So it was like the
middle of the month.

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:37.170
So I got on the phone, Hello.

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:40.530
And this 12-year-old, who
was working on appointments

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:43.080
for the president, said--

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:45.847
I guess I wasn't enthusiastic
enough because he said--

00:11:45.847 --> 00:11:48.180
aren't you surprised to be
getting a call from the White

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:48.750
House?

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:50.493
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:50.493 --> 00:11:51.240
Ah.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:52.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:55.470
So we moved beyond
that, and he said

00:11:55.470 --> 00:11:57.990
that, I'm calling
because we're looking

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:01.830
at for the position of
archivist of the United States.

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:03.930
So this is a
presidential appointment.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:07.860
And my sense of things
at that point-- and even

00:12:07.860 --> 00:12:11.610
now-- is that presidential
appointments are usually

00:12:11.610 --> 00:12:15.060
someone who gave a lot of
money to the campaign that

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:18.640
elected the president, or is
a friend of the president,

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:21.580
but doesn't know anything
about the business

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:24.170
of that particular position.

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:26.110
So why on Earth are
you calling me--

00:12:26.110 --> 00:12:27.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:29.530
--who knows the
business and doesn't

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:30.830
meet those other criteria?

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:33.287
So he couldn't answer that.

00:12:33.287 --> 00:12:35.120
SARA STEFANI: Did you
actually ask him that?

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:35.912
DAVID FERRIERO: No.

00:12:35.912 --> 00:12:36.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:38.290
I said, I'm very
flattered, but you're

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:41.230
looking at the wrong
person and made it clear

00:12:41.230 --> 00:12:43.090
that this was the end
of the conversation.

00:12:43.090 --> 00:12:44.980
And he said, well,
would you think about it

00:12:44.980 --> 00:12:47.680
over the weekend, and
we'll talk again on Monday.

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:49.010
And I said, sure.

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:51.045
So he called Monday morning.

00:12:51.045 --> 00:12:52.420
And we had the
same conversation.

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:55.060
And 10 minutes later
an adult called.

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:59.530
The poor kid, Kyle Watkins, was
an undergraduate at Georgetown

00:12:59.530 --> 00:13:01.480
working on appointments.

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:02.770
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:13:02.770 --> 00:13:04.270
DAVID FERRIERO: He
wasn't in charge,

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.780
but he was the one who did
the research that found me.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:08.680
SARA STEFANI: Oh-ho.

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:10.180
DAVID FERRIERO: So
he got the honor

00:13:10.180 --> 00:13:13.510
of calling me to tell me all
this, and I treated him poorly.

00:13:13.510 --> 00:13:15.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:15.740 --> 00:13:17.980
So 10 minutes later
an adult called

00:13:17.980 --> 00:13:19.630
and asked if he could
come to New York

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:20.890
and talk to me about the job.

00:13:20.890 --> 00:13:24.880
And that week Tom
Wheeler, who turned out

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:28.780
to be the director
of the FCC later,

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:31.720
came and talked about what
the president was looking

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:35.500
for in the new archivist, and
how important the archives was

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:37.870
going to be in the
administration's

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:41.740
open government initiative.

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:43.900
And the more he talked,
the more excited

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:46.090
I got about the potential.

00:13:46.090 --> 00:13:47.860
And knowing that I
know the business,

00:13:47.860 --> 00:13:51.730
I was responsible for archives
at MIT, and Duke, and the New

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:52.960
York Public Library.

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:56.032
So it's not as if I
didn't know the business.

00:13:56.032 --> 00:13:57.490
SARA STEFANI: Right,
because people

00:13:57.490 --> 00:13:59.662
have pointed out that
you're the first librarian.

00:13:59.662 --> 00:14:01.120
DAVID FERRIERO:
Very controversial.

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:02.830
Let me tell you,
very controversial.

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:04.460
SARA STEFANI: For those of you
who aren't in the business--

00:14:04.460 --> 00:14:05.543
DAVID FERRIERO: Oh my god.

00:14:05.543 --> 00:14:07.840
SARA STEFANI: It actually
is kind of controversial.

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:10.007
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah there's
a woman named Harriet--

00:14:10.007 --> 00:14:12.700
who I'm still looking for-- when
my nomination was announced,

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:14.230
who said on some listserv--

00:14:14.230 --> 00:14:17.092
I can't remember which one it
was-- he's only a librarian.

00:14:17.092 --> 00:14:17.842
SARA STEFANI: Ooh.

00:14:17.842 --> 00:14:19.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:21.360
Welcome to the IU
libraries, everyone.

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:24.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:28.110
DAVID FERRIERO: But there
has been, historically,

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:31.110
a lot of, I wouldn't
say tension,

00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:34.470
but difference among the
librarians and archivists.

00:14:34.470 --> 00:14:36.000
It's the same business, please.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.110
It's the same business.

00:14:37.110 --> 00:14:39.843
Collect, protect, encourage
the use of, fill in the blank.

00:14:39.843 --> 00:14:40.635
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:14:40.635 --> 00:14:43.680


00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:45.570
So you were nominated
for the position

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:46.950
by President Barack Obama.

00:14:46.950 --> 00:14:47.950
DAVID FERRIERO: Exactly.

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:50.110
SARA STEFANI: But you served
under President Obama,

00:14:50.110 --> 00:14:52.500
President Trump, and
then President Biden.

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:53.490
So you've kind of--

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:55.323
DAVID FERRIERO: It's a
lifetime appointment.

00:14:55.323 --> 00:14:57.640
There is no term for the
archivists in the United

00:14:57.640 --> 00:14:59.130
States.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:02.310
So at the end of
an administration

00:15:02.310 --> 00:15:05.400
there are 4,000
presidential appointments.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:06.870
And at the end of
an administration

00:15:06.870 --> 00:15:08.400
4,000 people leave.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:12.900
And so if you have a
presidential appointment,

00:15:12.900 --> 00:15:15.210
you get a notice from
the incoming president

00:15:15.210 --> 00:15:18.160
asking you to submit
your resignation,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.460
except the archivist
doesn't get that notice.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.210
SARA STEFANI: Oh, well,
that's a job perk.

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:23.127
DAVID FERRIERO: Right.

00:15:23.127 --> 00:15:24.280
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:26.530
DAVID FERRIERO: So one
of the huge challenges

00:15:26.530 --> 00:15:28.270
for the National
Archives is to ensure

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.760
that those 4,000
people who are leaving

00:15:30.760 --> 00:15:33.100
are leaving their
records behind.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:34.030
SARA STEFANI: Right.

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:35.740
DAVID FERRIERO: And
more challenging

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:38.680
is to ensure that those
4,000 people coming in

00:15:38.680 --> 00:15:39.947
know what the rules are.

00:15:39.947 --> 00:15:40.780
SARA STEFANI: Right.

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:41.470
Yeah.

00:15:41.470 --> 00:15:44.740
So you kind of touched
on this a little bit,

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:48.385
but you were nominated in--

00:15:48.385 --> 00:15:53.110
I think it was July
of 2009, correct?

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:57.460
And you were confirmed-- so
all presidential appointments

00:15:57.460 --> 00:16:00.850
have to be vetted by the
United States Senate.

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:03.220
There are confirmation hearings.

00:16:03.220 --> 00:16:06.730
Some of you might have
watched them on CNN or c-span.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:11.353
So everyone has to go
through the whole grilling

00:16:11.353 --> 00:16:12.520
process of having a hearing.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:13.770
DAVID FERRIERO: Very Invasive.

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:16.630
SARA STEFANI: Right, and
so you were actually--

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:21.040
I think that you were
nominated in July of 2009

00:16:21.040 --> 00:16:22.570
and then confirmed in November.

00:16:22.570 --> 00:16:23.020
DAVID FERRIERO: November

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:24.940
SARA STEFANI: So essentially
three months later.

00:16:24.940 --> 00:16:25.720
DAVID FERRIERO: Right

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:28.053
SARA STEFANI: The current
Archivist of the United States

00:16:28.053 --> 00:16:31.450
was nominated in, I
think, August of 2022

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:34.960
and wasn't confirmed
until May of 2023.

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:39.280
So it took nine months
to get her confirmed.

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:41.950
So what is that process like?

00:16:41.950 --> 00:16:45.910
What is it like to be nominated
and go through that kind of--

00:16:45.910 --> 00:16:47.950
DAVID FERRIERO: As I
said, it's very invasive.

00:16:47.950 --> 00:16:52.180


00:16:52.180 --> 00:16:54.800
So when Tom left
my office, he said,

00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:56.860
would you come to Washington
and talk some more?

00:16:56.860 --> 00:16:59.830
And that's when I met
with the full committee

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:02.360
at the White House and
talked about the job.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:06.368
And as I was leaving
the room, David Jacobson

00:17:06.368 --> 00:17:08.780
who was the head of that--

00:17:08.780 --> 00:17:12.579
Who was Kyle's boss said, so can
we consider you our candidate.

00:17:12.579 --> 00:17:13.540
And I said, yes.

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:15.670
And at that point
it was locked down.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:17.740
I couldn't talk to
anyone except my wife

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:19.390
about what was going on.

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:23.230
And that launched an
investigative process.

00:17:23.230 --> 00:17:26.470
FBI agents spread out
across the country talking

00:17:26.470 --> 00:17:29.470
to anyone I ever had known.

00:17:29.470 --> 00:17:35.540
And I kept getting these emails
from folks, friends saying,

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:37.780
what the hell is going on?

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:39.640
The FBI is at my door.

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:40.810
SARA STEFANI: Oh no.

00:17:40.810 --> 00:17:42.370
That is not what
you want to hear.

00:17:42.370 --> 00:17:43.745
DAVID FERRIERO:
All they can tell

00:17:43.745 --> 00:17:45.742
me is that it's not a
criminal investigation.

00:17:45.742 --> 00:17:46.450
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:17:46.450 --> 00:17:48.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:49.360
Thanks, yeah.

00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:52.600
DAVID FERRIERO: So I
passed those tests.

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:57.310
And then the next
phase is you have

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:00.550
to meet with every member
of the Senate Committee

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:01.690
that's voting on you.

00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:07.430
So a White House
shepherd and I visited

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:09.050
each member of the committee.

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:13.940
And my favorite visit was
with an unnamed Senator who

00:18:13.940 --> 00:18:15.257
asked me the killer question.

00:18:15.257 --> 00:18:16.340
SARA STEFANI: Which state?

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:17.990
DAVID FERRIERO: I'm not even
going to mention the state.

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:18.375
SARA STEFANI: I'm just kidding.

00:18:18.375 --> 00:18:18.760
[LAUGHS]

00:18:18.760 --> 00:18:20.843
DAVID FERRIERO: They asked
me the killer question,

00:18:20.843 --> 00:18:23.790
so why is it that you want to
be the architect of the United

00:18:23.790 --> 00:18:24.290
States?

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:24.998
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:18:24.998 --> 00:18:27.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:28.280
Yeah.

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:32.508
And you said, because I
like domes and columns.

00:18:32.508 --> 00:18:34.550
DAVID FERRIERO: No, I
pretended he said archivist

00:18:34.550 --> 00:18:38.650
and I talked about his
records, his papers.

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:41.910
And as we were leaving, the
shepherd turned to me and said,

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:43.250
did he say architect?

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:44.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:44.450 --> 00:18:47.088
SARA STEFANI: Because there is
an archivist-- or architect.

00:18:47.088 --> 00:18:48.380
DAVID FERRIERO: Of the Capitol.

00:18:48.380 --> 00:18:49.588
SARA STEFANI: Of the Capitol.

00:18:49.588 --> 00:18:50.210
Right, so.

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.770
DAVID FERRIERO: Not architect
of the United States.

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:52.070
SARA STEFANI: No,no,no.

00:18:52.070 --> 00:18:53.760
No architect of
the United States.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:56.180
So.

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:58.670
DAVID FERRIERO: So
then as a hearing.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:03.830
And I think I'm
the last person who

00:19:03.830 --> 00:19:06.708
had a swift appointment and
then a vote by the full Senate.

00:19:06.708 --> 00:19:07.500
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:08.292
You know, because--

00:19:08.292 --> 00:19:12.360
DAVID FERRIERO: But as
you've seen recently,

00:19:12.360 --> 00:19:15.750
any member of the Senate could
put a hold on a nomination.

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:16.500
SARA STEFANI: Yeah

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:18.840
DAVID FERRIERO: And Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:20.245
put a hold on my nomination.

00:19:20.245 --> 00:19:21.120
SARA STEFANI: Really?

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:22.020
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah.

00:19:22.020 --> 00:19:24.015
The White House
couldn't figure out--

00:19:24.015 --> 00:19:25.890
nobody could figure out
what the problem was.

00:19:25.890 --> 00:19:30.270
So they sent me to meet with
Lamar, who was very embarrassed

00:19:30.270 --> 00:19:32.100
that he had put a hold on it.

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:35.610
But it turns out that
one of his constituents

00:19:35.610 --> 00:19:39.180
reported that the director
of the Nixon Library

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:41.970
was saying some pretty
anti-Nixon things,

00:19:41.970 --> 00:19:45.490
and he thought I
should know about that.

00:19:45.490 --> 00:19:47.010
And once he got
that off the table,

00:19:47.010 --> 00:19:49.680
then we had a wonderful
conversation about his--

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:53.940
he used to be a president of
the University of Tennessee.

00:19:53.940 --> 00:19:57.180
So we talked about
higher education.

00:19:57.180 --> 00:19:59.640
He really embarrassed
because his wife, Honey,

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:01.850
was on the National
Archives Foundation board.

00:20:01.850 --> 00:20:02.850
SARA STEFANI: Ooh-ho-ho.

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:05.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:07.050
DAVID FERRIERO: So she
wasn't happy about him

00:20:07.050 --> 00:20:08.020
putting a hold on it.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:11.860
So as soon as I left the
office, they lifted the hold.

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:18.748
And I think it was the last
unanimous vote on a nomination.

00:20:18.748 --> 00:20:19.540
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:20.410
Well, yeah.

00:20:20.410 --> 00:20:23.470
Because, like I said, the
current Archivist of the United

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:25.000
States, it was very con--

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:28.190
Not, I think, because of her.

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:28.690
But--

00:20:28.690 --> 00:20:30.880
DAVID FERRIERO: No,
it's the dysfunction

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:36.130
of the Hill in terms of
the non-partisan approach

00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:36.970
to everything.

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:38.380
SARA STEFANI: Right.

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:42.220
So just to clarify for everyone.

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:45.460
So you essentially
are the director

00:20:45.460 --> 00:20:47.440
and the head of the
National Archives, right.

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:49.480
Technically the National
Archives and Records

00:20:49.480 --> 00:20:50.890
Administration.

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:53.960
And I kind of, and
correct me if I'm wrong,

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:56.560
but I think part
of the reason why

00:20:56.560 --> 00:21:01.060
there is such an invasive
process for vetting

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:04.030
the potential Archivist
of the United States,

00:21:04.030 --> 00:21:09.400
and sending the FBI, and finding
out everything from everyone

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:14.440
who ever knew you is because
you have access to some really

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:17.200
important documents.

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:17.867
No is this not--

00:21:17.867 --> 00:21:19.492
DAVID FERRIERO: The
process is the same

00:21:19.492 --> 00:21:20.867
for any presidential
appointment.

00:21:20.867 --> 00:21:21.825
SARA STEFANI: Oh, Yeah.

00:21:21.825 --> 00:21:22.720
Well no, I know that.

00:21:22.720 --> 00:21:25.420
But I guess it's
this idea that they

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:28.090
don't want anyone, any
presidential appointment,

00:21:28.090 --> 00:21:29.810
to be in a position
to be blackmailed--

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:31.060
DAVID FERRIERO: Oh yeah, sure.

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:32.977
SARA STEFANI: --or to
have something over you,

00:21:32.977 --> 00:21:37.840
or be able to leak documents,
or do anything like this.

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:40.580
And in your case, with
the National Archives,

00:21:40.580 --> 00:21:42.940
this is the home of
all of the founding

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:45.220
documents of this country.

00:21:45.220 --> 00:21:47.350
The Declaration of
Independence is there.

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:48.910
The US Constitution.

00:21:48.910 --> 00:21:51.220
The Bill of Rights.

00:21:51.220 --> 00:21:53.320
And they're on display.

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:56.650
They're just in this
wonderful display area.

00:21:56.650 --> 00:21:58.430
When I visited
several years ago,

00:21:58.430 --> 00:22:01.240
there were a lot of school kids.

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:05.350
It was a very popular
school kid destination.

00:22:05.350 --> 00:22:09.513
I actually read that you
wanted to do sleepovers.

00:22:09.513 --> 00:22:10.930
DAVID FERRIERO:
We did sleepovers.

00:22:10.930 --> 00:22:13.030
SARA STEFANI: Did you do
sleepovers in the rotunda?

00:22:13.030 --> 00:22:15.572
Was it just for school kids, or
were adults part of this too?

00:22:15.572 --> 00:22:17.410
DAVID FERRIERO:
Twice a year we did,

00:22:17.410 --> 00:22:18.712
for kids 8 to 12 years old.

00:22:18.712 --> 00:22:19.420
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:22:19.420 --> 00:22:22.000
DAVID FERRIERO: They had
to come with an adult.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:27.490
And we were limited
to, I think, 80 people.

00:22:27.490 --> 00:22:31.420
We started on a
Saturday night evening.

00:22:31.420 --> 00:22:34.600
We had a whole evening full
of activities for them,

00:22:34.600 --> 00:22:39.378
scavenger hunts, and
movies, and snacks, and--

00:22:39.378 --> 00:22:41.920
SARA STEFANI: Not peanut butter
and jelly sandwiches, though.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:43.150
Near the--

00:22:43.150 --> 00:22:46.270
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah, we
had a special area for food.

00:22:46.270 --> 00:22:47.680
Not in the rotunda--

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:48.850
SARA STEFANI: Not with
the Declaration of--

00:22:48.850 --> 00:22:49.350
OK.

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:50.200
DAVID FERRIERO: No.

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:53.800
And they brought sleeping
bags and stuff to sleep.

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:59.240
And lights out at 11 o'clock.

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:02.000
And they slept on the
floor of the rotunda

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.010
in the presence of the charters.

00:23:04.010 --> 00:23:05.504
SARA STEFANI: Wow.

00:23:05.504 --> 00:23:08.010
DAVID FERRIERO: And
on Sunday morning,

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:09.710
we did a pancake breakfast.

00:23:09.710 --> 00:23:10.832
I flipped pancakes.

00:23:10.832 --> 00:23:11.540
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:12.230
[LAUGHS]

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:13.730
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah,
it was a lot of fun.

00:23:13.730 --> 00:23:14.938
SARA STEFANI: Oh, that's so--

00:23:14.938 --> 00:23:17.450
And the way I
understand it is, that

00:23:17.450 --> 00:23:22.070
was part of a very important
initiative to you, which

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:26.810
was to make the collections
of the National Archives

00:23:26.810 --> 00:23:28.010
accessible to people.

