00:28:40.430 --> 00:28:41.900
DAVID FERRIERO: Exactly.

00:28:41.900 --> 00:28:45.200
So when I visited Saint Louis,
where our military records are,

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:49.820
there's a special vault
for high-end veterans.

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:53.930
Records that we want make
sure we want to make sure

00:28:53.930 --> 00:28:59.520
aren't tampered or messed up.

00:28:59.520 --> 00:29:01.360
Not that there's a
lot of that goes on.

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:03.940
But the VIP vaults.

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:06.360
So they took me on a
tour of the VIP vault

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:09.222
and handed me Elvis's
service record.

00:29:09.222 --> 00:29:09.930
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:12.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:12.270 --> 00:29:13.770
And was it?

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:17.502
Oh Yeah, so I think
that recently--

00:29:17.502 --> 00:29:19.210
and I want to see if
this is still true--

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:22.980
but recently we watched a
program from the New York

00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:24.690
Historical Society
that was an interview

00:29:24.690 --> 00:29:27.030
with the current Archivist
of the United States, Colleen

00:29:27.030 --> 00:29:27.570
Shogan.

00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:29.280
And she was asked
the question of what

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:33.000
is the most requested
and popular item.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.340
And she said it was
the photograph of Elvis

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:36.667
with President Richard Nixon.

00:29:36.667 --> 00:29:37.500
DAVID FERRIERO: Yes.

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:38.040
SARA STEFANI: Is that?

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:39.060
DAVID FERRIERO:
It's a great story.

00:29:39.060 --> 00:29:39.480
SARA STEFANI: Yeah?

00:29:39.480 --> 00:29:40.210
DAVID FERRIERO: You
want to hear it?

00:29:40.210 --> 00:29:40.830
SARA STEFANI: Absolutely.

00:29:40.830 --> 00:29:41.380
DAVID FERRIERO: OK.

00:29:41.380 --> 00:29:42.922
SARA STEFANI: Do
you want to hear it?

00:29:42.922 --> 00:29:44.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:44.220 --> 00:29:49.380
DAVID FERRIERO: So
Elvis collected badges.

00:29:49.380 --> 00:29:53.400
And he had badges from
all over the country.

00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:57.570
And the one that he really
wanted was an FBI badge,

00:29:57.570 --> 00:30:00.300
and the FBI refused
to give him a badge.

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:08.370
So he took it upon himself
to fly from Los Angeles--

00:30:08.370 --> 00:30:09.480
he was on the West Coast.

00:30:09.480 --> 00:30:13.710
He flew to Washington
on American Airlines

00:30:13.710 --> 00:30:17.700
because he asked the flight
attendant for stationery

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:22.980
to write a letter
to President Nixon,

00:30:22.980 --> 00:30:26.580
asking to meet with him
because he wanted to volunteer

00:30:26.580 --> 00:30:28.440
for his war on drugs.

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:30.030
Nothing about badges.

00:30:30.030 --> 00:30:31.350
Nothing about badges.

00:30:31.350 --> 00:30:32.250
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:30:32.250 --> 00:30:35.850
DAVID FERRIERO: And he and he
got into a cab at the airport

00:30:35.850 --> 00:30:39.480
and got delivered
to the West Wing

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:43.005
gate, where he handed the
letter in, which you can't do.

00:30:43.005 --> 00:30:44.130
They won't accept anything.

00:30:44.130 --> 00:30:48.180
So don't try and leave a letter
at the gate at the White House.

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:50.910
And it ended up in Bud Krogh--

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:53.220
Bud Krogh, who
was chief of Staff

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:56.940
to President Nixon
and a huge Elvis fan.

00:30:56.940 --> 00:30:59.070
It ended up in his hands.

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:04.760
And sure enough, Elvis was
invited, that afternoon,

00:31:04.760 --> 00:31:08.570
to come and to visit
with the president.

00:31:08.570 --> 00:31:12.150


00:31:12.150 --> 00:31:13.470
Bud did a program with us.

00:31:13.470 --> 00:31:17.280
And if you google Bud Krogh
Elvis National Archives,

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:19.650
you can watch this
wonderful conversation

00:31:19.650 --> 00:31:21.840
with Bud telling
the story of Nixon

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:23.550
not really knowing
who Elvis was.

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:26.670
And do I really have
to meet with him?

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:28.500
And all of this.

00:31:28.500 --> 00:31:31.590


00:31:31.590 --> 00:31:34.410
There wasn't any conversation
about drugs or anything

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:38.070
in this one on one
with the president,

00:31:38.070 --> 00:31:40.920
but he got to the point
where he wanted a badge.

00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:43.830
He really wanted an FBI badge,
so he asked Nixon for it.

00:31:43.830 --> 00:31:46.620
And Nixon turned to Bud
and said, can I do that?

00:31:46.620 --> 00:31:48.810
And Bud Krogh says,
of course you can.

00:31:48.810 --> 00:31:49.710
You're the president.

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:50.725
So guess what?

00:31:50.725 --> 00:31:52.350
SARA STEFANI: Did he
get the FBI badge?

00:31:52.350 --> 00:31:53.910
DAVID FERRIERO: He
got the FBI badge.

00:31:53.910 --> 00:31:56.340
And then Bud tells
the story of--

00:31:56.340 --> 00:31:58.380
this is true of every president.

00:31:58.380 --> 00:32:01.920
The resolute desk
has a bottom drawer

00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:05.730
full of gifts that the
president gives to visitors

00:32:05.730 --> 00:32:08.160
and they're arranged
in priority order,

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:11.320
for the cheap stuff at the front
and the really expensive stuff

00:32:11.320 --> 00:32:12.280
at the back.

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:16.450
So Nixon said to Elvis, I
want to give you a gift.

00:32:16.450 --> 00:32:18.850
So Elvis got up out of
his chair and went around

00:32:18.850 --> 00:32:22.930
the back of the desk instead
of waiting for the president.

00:32:22.930 --> 00:32:24.700
And he goes and pulls up--

00:32:24.700 --> 00:32:27.070
I forget what he pulled
out-- but went right

00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:29.170
to the back of the
drawer and pulled out

00:32:29.170 --> 00:32:30.362
the most expensive stuff.

00:32:30.362 --> 00:32:31.570
SARA STEFANI: The good stuff.

00:32:31.570 --> 00:32:32.230
Yeah.

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:34.270
[LAUGHS]

00:32:34.270 --> 00:32:38.140
DAVID FERRIERO: So we have the
letter in the Nixon Library.

00:32:38.140 --> 00:32:42.040
We have the letter that Elvis
wrote and wonderful pictures.

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:45.850
And the picture is on shower
curtains, coffee mugs.

00:32:45.850 --> 00:32:48.340
It's on T-shirts, sweatshirts.

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:50.770
It's on everything.

00:32:50.770 --> 00:32:55.600
SARA STEFANI: And so
along those lines,

00:32:55.600 --> 00:32:59.710
where do Presidential records
and Presidential papers

00:32:59.710 --> 00:33:03.430
fit in to all of this?

00:33:03.430 --> 00:33:08.260
DAVID FERRIERO: As of 1978,
because President Nixon

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:12.670
considered his papers
private, not public--

00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:14.710
and the whole Watergate thing--

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:18.610
Congress decided we need
to codify this and make

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:21.110
it clear that Presidential
records are public records.

00:33:21.110 --> 00:33:24.430
So they belong to the
federal government.

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:28.150
And the way it
works is the records

00:33:28.150 --> 00:33:32.320
are maintained in
the White House

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:35.170
during the administration.

00:33:35.170 --> 00:33:38.650
And it isn't until
the inauguration

00:33:38.650 --> 00:33:41.950
of the new president,
during that ceremony,

00:33:41.950 --> 00:33:45.280
that the records are transferred
to the National Archives.

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:48.718
They stay in the White
House until then.

00:33:48.718 --> 00:33:51.010
SARA STEFANI: So you kind of
touched on it a little bit

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:54.640
about the personal ownership
versus the public ownership,

00:33:54.640 --> 00:33:57.130
because for centuries--

00:33:57.130 --> 00:34:01.150
I mean 1 and 1/2
centuries, 150 years--

00:34:01.150 --> 00:34:03.822
Presidential papers were
considered personal property.

00:34:03.822 --> 00:34:06.280
DAVID FERRIERO: And they're
scattered all over the country.

00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:06.760
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:09.010
DAVID FERRIERO: Library of
Congress has a lot of them.

00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:12.790
But it wasn't until
FDR, actually,

00:34:12.790 --> 00:34:15.429
who had the first
Presidential Library.

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:18.820
I'm convinced that FDR
was a closet archivist,

00:34:18.820 --> 00:34:20.469
because he really paid--

00:34:20.469 --> 00:34:22.060
SARA STEFANI: There are a lot
of them out there, actually.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:23.143
DAVID FERRIERO: I know it.

00:34:23.143 --> 00:34:25.330
He really paid attention
to organization.

00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:29.139
And he actually-- you probably
don't know this-- but,

00:34:29.139 --> 00:34:33.909
you archivists, he created
the prototype phase box

00:34:33.909 --> 00:34:35.675
that you now store
your records in.

00:34:35.675 --> 00:34:36.550
SARA STEFANI: Really?

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:38.560
DAVID FERRIERO: It
wasn't with acid free--

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:39.580
SARA STEFANI: The archivists
are really excited about this.

00:34:39.580 --> 00:34:40.639
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:40.639 --> 00:34:43.097
DAVID FERRIERO: It wasn't with
acid free paper or anything,

00:34:43.097 --> 00:34:44.710
but it's the same box.

