so Franklin Roosevelt
was the first president

00:34:57.800 --> 00:35:00.240
to start a Presidential
Library, right.

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.240
So it's to look at
everything and say, Wow, I've

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:03.830
got a lot of cool stuff.

00:35:03.830 --> 00:35:06.270
I should make it accessible
to the American people.

00:35:06.270 --> 00:35:08.630
And so he established
a library and a museum.

00:35:08.630 --> 00:35:13.430
And he had tons of gifts,
and memorabilia, and chairs,

00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:14.390
and I don't know what.

00:35:14.390 --> 00:35:17.420
And the archivist who was
working with him said, do you

00:35:17.420 --> 00:35:18.943
really need all of this?

00:35:18.943 --> 00:35:21.110
Do you really want to put
all of this in the museum?

00:35:21.110 --> 00:35:23.630
And he said, if people
are going to pay a quarter

00:35:23.630 --> 00:35:27.950
to come to this library,
they need to see some stuff.

00:35:27.950 --> 00:35:29.630
They're paying a quarter.

00:35:29.630 --> 00:35:32.960
But could you talk a little
bit about what a Presidential

00:35:32.960 --> 00:35:37.010
Library is versus the
Presidential Records

00:35:37.010 --> 00:35:38.527
that go into the
National Archives

00:35:38.527 --> 00:35:39.860
and what that system looks like.

00:35:39.860 --> 00:35:41.330
DAVID FERRIERO:
It's a combination.

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:44.430
It's artifacts and records.

00:35:44.430 --> 00:35:50.890
So state gifts and lots of
gifts from the American public

00:35:50.890 --> 00:35:54.100
all become part of-- those
are considered records--

00:35:54.100 --> 00:35:58.210
and become part of the museum
aspect of the Presidential

00:35:58.210 --> 00:35:59.230
Library.

00:35:59.230 --> 00:36:01.600
We have a wonderful--

00:36:01.600 --> 00:36:05.320
the largest collection of
macaroni paintings in the world

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:07.420
are in our
Presidential Libraries.

00:36:07.420 --> 00:36:10.450
We have every shoe that
Hillary Clinton ever wore.

00:36:10.450 --> 00:36:12.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:17.350
We have a lot of First
Lady [LAUGHS] wardrobes.

00:36:17.350 --> 00:36:22.295
And Hillary Clinton is still
delivering shoes to the Clinton

00:36:22.295 --> 00:36:23.170
Presidential Library.

00:36:23.170 --> 00:36:26.480


00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:28.240
Very strange collections.

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:30.190
SARA STEFANI: But the
public can visit them.

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:30.610
DAVID FERRIERO: Yes.

00:36:30.610 --> 00:36:31.930
SARA STEFANI: And
they have exhibitions.

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:32.930
DAVID FERRIERO: Exactly.

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:34.600
SARA STEFANI: And you
can see the shoes.

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:35.940
Can you try them on though?

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:37.720
DAVID FERRIERO: No.

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:39.638
After I had done my
first tour of all

00:36:39.638 --> 00:36:41.680
the Presidential Libraries
and seen all of these,

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:43.270
I started putting
things together

00:36:43.270 --> 00:36:47.900
and threatened to do a first
lady shoe exhibit from--

00:36:47.900 --> 00:36:50.150
DIANE DALLIS-COMENTALE: I
think the Met did an exhibit

00:36:50.150 --> 00:36:51.540
on first lady dresses.

00:36:51.540 --> 00:36:53.570
So I don't know why
you wouldn't do shoes.

00:36:53.570 --> 00:36:54.380
DAVID FERRIERO: We
could do that too.

00:36:54.380 --> 00:36:54.850
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:55.760
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah,
we could do that too.

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:58.790
SARA STEFANI: So one of the
things that you also mentioned,

00:36:58.790 --> 00:37:01.220
that is in the
event description,

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:07.160
that I do want to talk about is
the theme for IU's Themester.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:09.860
This last Themester is
Lux et Veritas, right,

00:37:09.860 --> 00:37:13.880
which translates
into light and truth.

00:37:13.880 --> 00:37:18.740
It's also actually part of
the motto on the official seal

00:37:18.740 --> 00:37:20.810
of Indiana University.

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:23.660
And I know that when
my colleagues first

00:37:23.660 --> 00:37:26.690
had this idea of celebrating
this last Themester

00:37:26.690 --> 00:37:31.610
and inviting you, they had this
really nice idea of shining

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:37.970
the light of truth onto records,
and history, and archives,

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:40.230
and things along those lines.

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:42.440
And you've talked
about open government

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:43.820
and the open government system.

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:47.640
Can you talk a little
bit of what that means.

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.210
What does open government
mean, and why is it important?

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:53.460
Why is it an
important principle?

00:37:53.460 --> 00:37:58.370
DAVID FERRIERO: So in the Obama
language for open government,

00:37:58.370 --> 00:38:01.880
it was transparency,
participation,

00:38:01.880 --> 00:38:02.720
and collaboration.

00:38:02.720 --> 00:38:07.190
Those are the three linchpins
of what open government means.

00:38:07.190 --> 00:38:10.190
And for the National
Archives, we

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:12.440
tried hard to figure
out ways that we

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:14.580
could fulfill that vision.

00:38:14.580 --> 00:38:17.030
So on his first day in
office, the president

00:38:17.030 --> 00:38:21.440
met with his senior staff
and made the statement

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:24.050
that the government doesn't
have all the answers,

00:38:24.050 --> 00:38:27.110
and we need to figure out ways
to engage the American public

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:28.830
in doing our work.

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:32.150
So we took that very seriously
at the National Archives

00:38:32.150 --> 00:38:34.100
and worked on and
thought about ways

00:38:34.100 --> 00:38:37.400
that we could engage
the public in the work

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:41.030
that we do, which resulted in
the creation of the Citizen

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:45.560
Archivist project, where we have
opportunities for the public

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:50.790
to help us, in a number of ways,
in making access to our records

00:38:50.790 --> 00:38:51.610
better.

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:54.390
So, as you probably
know, cursive

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:57.030
isn't taught much
in schools anymore.

00:38:57.030 --> 00:39:01.470
And about 80% of the Federal
Records are in cursive.

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:04.800
So we have kids now,
and their parents

00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:07.620
in lots of cases, who
can't read these records.

00:39:07.620 --> 00:39:09.510
And in fact, I was
talking to a couple

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:12.270
of adults last night who
couldn't read records,

00:39:12.270 --> 00:39:13.287
couldn't read cursive.

00:39:13.287 --> 00:39:15.120
SARA STEFANI: Or even
from the 19th century,

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:18.030
even if you can read cursive,
it's a different kind

00:39:18.030 --> 00:39:18.830
and it's--

00:39:18.830 --> 00:39:20.580
DAVID FERRIERO: Don't
give me any excuses.

00:39:20.580 --> 00:39:21.747
SARA STEFANI: OK, all right.

00:39:21.747 --> 00:39:22.482
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:22.482 --> 00:39:23.190
I take that back.

00:39:23.190 --> 00:39:24.990
DAVID FERRIERO: So we
have loaded thousands

00:39:24.990 --> 00:39:27.510
of records in the Citizen
Archivist Dashboard

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:29.700
and you can go in and
transcribe for us.

00:39:29.700 --> 00:39:31.620
And we've got folks
from, actually,

00:39:31.620 --> 00:39:34.750
around the world who are
participating in this.

00:39:34.750 --> 00:39:38.790
And to date, we have I think
the figure is something

00:39:38.790 --> 00:39:44.655
like 250 million transcriptions
have been done of our records.

00:39:44.655 --> 00:39:47.280
SARA STEFANI: And this is just,
when you say Citizen Archivist,

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:52.260
this is just people,
just the public.

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:55.350
Well, I mean, these are not
necessarily employees of NARA.

00:39:55.350 --> 00:39:57.142
DAVID FERRIERO: There's
a wonderful nursing

00:39:57.142 --> 00:39:59.980
home in Massachusetts that
has adopted this project.

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:01.472
And they do they
do transcriptions.

00:40:01.472 --> 00:40:03.180
SARA STEFANI: So this
is for anyone who's

00:40:03.180 --> 00:40:05.130
interested in getting involved.

00:40:05.130 --> 00:40:06.270
Is it still going?

00:40:06.270 --> 00:40:07.470
Can people still get in--

00:40:07.470 --> 00:40:07.920
DAVID FERRIERO: Oh Yeah

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:09.390
SARA STEFANI: How they get
involved in the project?

00:40:09.390 --> 00:40:10.557
DAVID FERRIERO: Archives.gov

00:40:10.557 --> 00:40:12.610
SARA STEFANI: Archives.gov OK.

00:40:12.610 --> 00:40:15.300
Do you do crowdsourcing
like, with photographs?

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:16.800
DAVID FERRIERO: Oh
yeah, we do that.

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:17.300
Yeah.

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:19.587
There are several
different options.

00:40:19.587 --> 00:40:20.670
You can do transcriptions.

00:40:20.670 --> 00:40:22.680
You can tag photos.

00:40:22.680 --> 00:40:25.020
As I said, we have 43
million photographs

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:27.430
and not very well described.

00:40:27.430 --> 00:40:30.180
So we've loaded
thousands of photographs

00:40:30.180 --> 00:40:34.410
where people are tagging people
that they recognize, or places

00:40:34.410 --> 00:40:37.470
if they recognize, or whatever
information they might

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:41.040
have about the photograph.

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:43.200
SARA STEFANI: So what
is the result of this.

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:46.830
How many people have been
involved as Citizen Archivists.

00:40:46.830 --> 00:40:50.145
And has NARA been
pleased with the results?

00:40:50.145 --> 00:40:51.770
DAVID FERRIERO: The
results have been--

00:40:51.770 --> 00:40:53.103
SARA STEFANI: How's the quality?

00:40:53.103 --> 00:40:55.320
DAVID FERRIERO: I can't
give you numbers of people.

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:59.330
But we've been very
pleased with the quality

00:40:59.330 --> 00:41:00.800
of the transcriptions
and each one

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:04.680
is checked to make sure
that it's accurate.

00:41:04.680 --> 00:41:08.540
Another way that we've focused
on-- this came up in my meeting

00:41:08.540 --> 00:41:10.040
with the students today.

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:13.220


00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:18.740
Every attempt is to make our
content accessible in any way

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:19.500
we possibly can.

00:41:19.500 --> 00:41:25.040
So we've devoted a lot of work,
time, and effort on Wikipedia.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:25.790
SARA STEFANI: Yeah

00:41:25.790 --> 00:41:28.415
DAVID FERRIERO: Hired the first
federal Wikipedian in residence

00:41:28.415 --> 00:41:31.400
was part of the
National Archives staff,

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:36.020
who had the dual role of
helping us create those links

00:41:36.020 --> 00:41:40.200
but also educating the staff
about the power of Wikipedia.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:48.380
So now our processing
folks link record groups

00:41:48.380 --> 00:41:52.400
to articles in Wikipedia.

00:41:52.400 --> 00:41:56.030
And there are probably
in the neighborhood

00:41:56.030 --> 00:42:01.010
of 4,000 to 5,000
Wikipedia records that

00:42:01.010 --> 00:42:05.360
have content that have links
from the National Archives.

00:42:05.360 --> 00:42:13.160
And we get three billion hits a
year from those Wikipedia hits.

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:15.050
SARA STEFANI: Well,
and also, you also

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:19.970
initiated a huge social
media initiative as well.

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:21.410
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah.

00:42:21.410 --> 00:42:24.980
When I was coming to
Washington for one

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:28.100
of those meetings on the Hill
with the Senate Committee.

00:42:28.100 --> 00:42:31.550
I'm not even the archivist yet,
but I'm reading the New York

00:42:31.550 --> 00:42:35.780
Times and there's this article
about the White House letting

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:40.370
an RFP with help on
their social media.

00:42:40.370 --> 00:42:41.150
Archiving.

00:42:41.150 --> 00:42:42.170
Archiving social media.

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:43.310
SARA STEFANI: Oh,
archiving social media.

00:42:43.310 --> 00:42:45.440
DAVID FERRIERO: And I'm saying
to myself, oh wait a minute.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:46.770
Where's the National Archives?

00:42:46.770 --> 00:42:48.680
Why aren't they all over this?

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:51.600
And it turns out that the
National Archives wasn't doing

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:53.860
anything with social media.

00:42:53.860 --> 00:42:57.240
And this is 2009.

00:42:57.240 --> 00:43:00.180
And I discovered that there
was a small group of folks

00:43:00.180 --> 00:43:03.690
who were interested
in social media

00:43:03.690 --> 00:43:09.690
and were meeting in secret
to talk about their dreams

00:43:09.690 --> 00:43:12.750
about how they might
use social media.

00:43:12.750 --> 00:43:15.855
And I heard about
this, and I walked

00:43:15.855 --> 00:43:16.980
into one of their meetings.

00:43:16.980 --> 00:43:19.140
And they thought
they were busted.

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:20.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:20.580 --> 00:43:22.560
And we sat down and had
a great conversation.

00:43:22.560 --> 00:43:27.810
And at that meeting I
authorized the purchase

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:38.310
of iPads and iPhones,
25 to fool around.

00:43:38.310 --> 00:43:40.170
And let's get started here.

00:43:40.170 --> 00:43:45.210
And the next morning I got a
call from my CIO, who said,

00:43:45.210 --> 00:43:47.310
I understand you want
iPads and iPhones.

00:43:47.310 --> 00:43:49.030
And I said, Yeah,
isn't it exciting.

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:51.040
We're going to experiment
and blah, blah, blah.

00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:54.790
And she said, well, you know, we
don't support that technology.

00:43:54.790 --> 00:43:55.980
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:43:55.980 --> 00:43:57.007
IPads and iPhones?

00:43:57.007 --> 00:43:58.590
DAVID FERRIERO: Then
I said, you know,

00:43:58.590 --> 00:44:00.150
the best part about
this technology

00:44:00.150 --> 00:44:01.483
is it doesn't need your support.

00:44:01.483 --> 00:44:04.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:04.770 --> 00:44:09.330
And the next call I got
was from acquisitions,

00:44:09.330 --> 00:44:11.370
I understand you want
iPhones and iPads.

00:44:11.370 --> 00:44:12.467
I say, isn't it exciting.

00:44:12.467 --> 00:44:13.800
We're going to be experimenting.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:14.367
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:14.367 --> 00:44:15.450
SARA STEFANI: I like this.

00:44:15.450 --> 00:44:16.950
Just keep repeating it.

00:44:16.950 --> 00:44:18.365
Yeah.

00:44:18.365 --> 00:44:19.990
DAVID FERRIERO:
That'll take 13 months.

00:44:19.990 --> 00:44:21.750
13 months.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:23.520
I said, no, that's
not good enough.

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:25.320
Uh-Uh, that doesn't work for me.

00:44:25.320 --> 00:44:27.370
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:27.370 --> 00:44:29.340
SARA STEFANI: I
actually had a student--

00:44:29.340 --> 00:44:31.110
I hope she's here today, but--

00:44:31.110 --> 00:44:33.690
contact me yesterday
from the IDS

00:44:33.690 --> 00:44:36.270
with the Indiana Daily Student,
which is a student newspaper.

00:44:36.270 --> 00:44:38.970
And she asked me a really
interesting question.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:43.350
She asked me what I found
most interesting or inspiring

00:44:43.350 --> 00:44:44.190
about you.

00:44:44.190 --> 00:44:48.760
And I have to say that
my answer was actually

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:51.670
the "Gighy" or
"Jiphy," depending

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:54.610
on how you pronounce it, the
Giphy Channel for the National

00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:55.480
Archives.

00:44:55.480 --> 00:44:57.440
Because I checked it out.

00:44:57.440 --> 00:44:58.030
It's amazing.

00:44:58.030 --> 00:45:02.350
There are 1,500 JIFs
or GIFs, depending

00:45:02.350 --> 00:45:07.390
on your preference,
that have been uploaded

00:45:07.390 --> 00:45:11.170
and over 5.3 billion views.

00:45:11.170 --> 00:45:12.220
Billion.

00:45:12.220 --> 00:45:16.780
And it's amazing because there
are things from World War One,

00:45:16.780 --> 00:45:20.530
World War Two, but
also space exploration,

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:24.940
and the Apollo 11 mission,
and civil rights movement,

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:27.190
and women's suffrage.

00:45:27.190 --> 00:45:31.630
But also kids
sledding, and holidays,

00:45:31.630 --> 00:45:35.783
and my favorite, which is
the dancing dogs, Waffles

00:45:35.783 --> 00:45:36.325
and Dempsey--

00:45:36.325 --> 00:45:37.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:38.740
--who are wearing little tutus.

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:43.240
And what I said
was that, to me it

00:45:43.240 --> 00:45:47.350
is making the federal government
and the National Archives

00:45:47.350 --> 00:45:49.120
more accessible.

00:45:49.120 --> 00:45:53.290
And it is saying to
people, everyone's welcome.

00:45:53.290 --> 00:45:58.450
We're not just this imposing
building on Pennsylvania Avenue

00:45:58.450 --> 00:45:59.800
but we're you.

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:01.240
We're About you.

00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:03.970
So is this kind of
something that you felt--

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:08.830
how do you feel that this
helped with NARA's image?

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:10.840
DAVID FERRIERO: First of
all, it was unleashing

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:13.630
the talent within the
Agency that these folks have

00:46:13.630 --> 00:46:16.570
been dreaming about things
to do with social media.

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:21.550
As I said, in 2009 we were not
on any social media platforms.

00:46:21.550 --> 00:46:23.440
And the argument I
made with the staff

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:26.380
was, we are responsible
for providing

00:46:26.380 --> 00:46:30.910
guidance to the agencies
about the records

00:46:30.910 --> 00:46:34.130
implications of their
use of social media.

00:46:34.130 --> 00:46:36.430
And if we're not using
this stuff ourselves,

00:46:36.430 --> 00:46:38.930
how are we possibly
going to do that?

00:46:38.930 --> 00:46:47.380
So we're now on 16 platforms
and the staff is energized,

00:46:47.380 --> 00:46:51.370
and it has spread
to State Archives

00:46:51.370 --> 00:46:55.792
and other archives have been
following what we're doing.

00:46:55.792 --> 00:46:57.250
SARA STEFANI: Well,
and I noticed--

00:46:57.250 --> 00:46:58.870
and we'll start
with the questions--

00:46:58.870 --> 00:47:04.840
but I also noticed that the
Trump Presidential Library

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:06.638
has an archive of his tweets.

00:47:06.638 --> 00:47:07.930
DAVID FERRIERO: Yes, of course.

00:47:07.930 --> 00:47:11.860
SARA STEFANI: So social
media is actually

00:47:11.860 --> 00:47:15.010
an important social
phenomenon that

00:47:15.010 --> 00:47:18.730
is woven into the nation's
history and the Presidential

00:47:18.730 --> 00:47:20.350
Records.

