avoided a government shutdown,
you saw the National Archives

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:32.590
through a few shutdowns.

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:38.920
How did these impact the work
of NARA, short and long term?

00:47:38.920 --> 00:47:41.590
DAVID FERRIERO: It's
a horrible situation

00:47:41.590 --> 00:47:45.970
because we have no idea how long
the shutdown is going to last.

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:49.490
That the staff by and large--

00:47:49.490 --> 00:47:52.360
we have, for the National
Archives it's 3,000 people

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:57.370
in 42 facilities in 17 states--

00:47:57.370 --> 00:47:59.830
most of them live
paycheck to paycheck.

00:47:59.830 --> 00:48:02.650
They're not getting paid,
and they have no idea

00:48:02.650 --> 00:48:05.290
how long this is going to last.

00:48:05.290 --> 00:48:08.920
For the longer ones, and we've
been through some longer ones,

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:13.060
people have actually left
and taken other jobs.

00:48:13.060 --> 00:48:18.430
But the damage it
does to people feeling

00:48:18.430 --> 00:48:21.940
good about working for the
government and the damage

00:48:21.940 --> 00:48:25.262
it does in recruiting
is really serious.

00:48:25.262 --> 00:48:27.220
SARA STEFANI: We talked
about this this morning

00:48:27.220 --> 00:48:29.260
because my mother
actually worked

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:33.100
for the federal government for
the Department of Agriculture.

00:48:33.100 --> 00:48:37.660
And she had to live
through several shutdowns

00:48:37.660 --> 00:48:38.840
as a single mother.

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:41.650
And so I've
experienced this, so.

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:43.330
Yeah.

00:48:43.330 --> 00:48:45.550
What you're saying about
tarnishing kind of work--

00:48:45.550 --> 00:48:47.300
anyway, all right.

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:47.900
Next question,

00:48:47.900 --> 00:48:49.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:51.620
My students are currently
reading and thinking

00:48:51.620 --> 00:48:52.670
about archives.

00:48:52.670 --> 00:48:55.160
It's a history gateway
course but they

00:48:55.160 --> 00:48:59.630
are deeply concerned about
access to historical materials.

00:48:59.630 --> 00:49:03.560
What was your role in getting
materials into the archives

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:06.320
from various departments
of the government?

00:49:06.320 --> 00:49:10.040


00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:14.200
DAVID FERRIERO: So way
back at the beginning,

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:18.310
when FDR signed the legislation
and created the National

00:49:18.310 --> 00:49:20.380
Archives, he really
took-- as you

00:49:20.380 --> 00:49:23.410
know I made that crack about
him being a closet archivist.

00:49:23.410 --> 00:49:27.370
But he really took an
interest in the archives,

00:49:27.370 --> 00:49:30.460
recruited the first
archivist, and made

00:49:30.460 --> 00:49:34.930
sure that archivist got what
he needed in terms of support.

00:49:34.930 --> 00:49:38.050
And that first archivist had
the job of wandering around town

00:49:38.050 --> 00:49:39.760
and figuring out where
the records were,

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:42.520
and hiring a staff,
and an architect,

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:44.455
and all that kind of stuff.

00:49:44.455 --> 00:49:55.840


00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:56.980
Read that again.

00:49:56.980 --> 00:49:58.185
SARA STEFANI: Oh, so.

00:49:58.185 --> 00:49:59.560
DAVID FERRIERO:
There was a point

00:49:59.560 --> 00:50:03.550
I was trying to make with
[LAUGHS] why we had to go back.

00:50:03.550 --> 00:50:04.810
Oh, because, OK.

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:08.680
So then this poor
archivist had the job

00:50:08.680 --> 00:50:10.990
of convincing agency
heads that this

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:12.793
is the new way of doing
business and you've

00:50:12.793 --> 00:50:13.960
got to give me your records.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:16.910
And you can imagine
how that went over.

00:50:16.910 --> 00:50:19.960
So FDR had to have a cabinet
meeting where he kind of laid

00:50:19.960 --> 00:50:22.968
down the law about
this is the way we're

00:50:22.968 --> 00:50:24.010
going to do business now.

00:50:24.010 --> 00:50:28.480
And the holdout then, and
to some extent still--

00:50:28.480 --> 00:50:30.910
not that I want to throw
anyone under the bus--

00:50:30.910 --> 00:50:31.600
SARA STEFANI: You're
retired, go ahead.

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:32.980
DAVID FERRIERO: --is
the State Department.

00:50:32.980 --> 00:50:33.688
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

00:50:33.688 --> 00:50:37.540
DAVID FERRIERO: So state
was a unhappy camper

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:40.720
at the very beginning, and
FDR took it upon himself

00:50:40.720 --> 00:50:42.520
one evening after hours.

00:50:42.520 --> 00:50:46.480
He wrote about this, and I
was in hysterics reading it.

00:50:46.480 --> 00:50:49.360
He had himself taken over
to the State Department.

00:50:49.360 --> 00:50:54.020
And he describes this long
corridor with filing cabinets.

00:50:54.020 --> 00:50:56.900
He wheels himself up
at random and pulls out

00:50:56.900 --> 00:51:03.170
a file on Mongolian ponies to
demonstrate that you perhaps

00:51:03.170 --> 00:51:06.140
don't need this file
on Mongolian ponies

00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:10.220
here in the State Department.

00:51:10.220 --> 00:51:12.530
And that's been a
problem ever since.

00:51:12.530 --> 00:51:16.730
That some agencies are--

00:51:16.730 --> 00:51:20.210
especially, I would say
the intelligence community.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:21.770
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:51:21.770 --> 00:51:25.580
Yeah, I guess I can
understand this reticence

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:28.070
when they're dealing with
intelligence and classified

00:51:28.070 --> 00:51:28.770
documents.

00:51:28.770 --> 00:51:31.640
DAVID FERRIERO: So this
Mongolian Pony thing

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:32.700
bothered me.

00:51:32.700 --> 00:51:36.950
And so I went to the staff
and said, so can you find it?

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:37.880
Do we have that?

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:38.660
We don't have it.

00:51:38.660 --> 00:51:39.500
We don't have it.

00:51:39.500 --> 00:51:39.800
SARA STEFANI: Yeah

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:41.383
DAVID FERRIERO: So
they still have it.

00:51:41.383 --> 00:51:44.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:44.730 --> 00:51:47.000
SARA STEFANI: Well, should
I submit a FOIA, Freedom

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:48.320
of Information Act request?

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:49.190
DAVID FERRIERO: That
would be fun, yeah.

00:51:49.190 --> 00:51:49.898
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:51:49.898 --> 00:51:50.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:55.280
How has the relationship between
historians and archivists

00:51:55.280 --> 00:51:57.965
changed over the
course of your career?

00:51:57.965 --> 00:52:03.350


00:52:03.350 --> 00:52:07.960
DAVID FERRIERO: I think they
have better access to records

00:52:07.960 --> 00:52:12.160
than they've had before.

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:22.920
I think we're good salespeople
for their product, what

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:24.180
they've written.

00:52:24.180 --> 00:52:30.480
I made it a point to do public
programs with any historian who

00:52:30.480 --> 00:52:33.960
used the records as a way of
demonstrating the value that we

00:52:33.960 --> 00:52:35.640
bring.

00:52:35.640 --> 00:52:37.140
And I think the
work that we've been

00:52:37.140 --> 00:52:39.810
doing in terms of
digitizing records

00:52:39.810 --> 00:52:46.020
has improved the speed with
which they can do research.

00:52:46.020 --> 00:52:48.480
SARA STEFANI: And there's
actually a parenthetical

00:52:48.480 --> 00:52:51.510
question here, where
the person says, here

00:52:51.510 --> 00:52:55.770
at IU we collaborate more
as guardians of the past,

00:52:55.770 --> 00:53:02.160
navigating a more political
and less resourced present day.

00:53:02.160 --> 00:53:03.390
DAVID FERRIERO: Interesting.

00:53:03.390 --> 00:53:04.500
That's a good way
of phrasing it.

00:53:04.500 --> 00:53:05.400
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:09.690
So as Guardians of the past,
navigating a more political

00:53:09.690 --> 00:53:12.180
and less resource present day.

00:53:12.180 --> 00:53:13.867
Did you feel that
when you were--

00:53:13.867 --> 00:53:14.950
DAVID FERRIERO: Definitely

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:15.430
SARA STEFANI: Yeah, archivist?

00:53:15.430 --> 00:53:16.555
DAVID FERRIERO: Definitely.

00:53:16.555 --> 00:53:19.280


00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:20.860
SARA STEFANI: Next
one, can you speak

00:53:20.860 --> 00:53:25.330
about archives in the age
of extreme climate change?

00:53:25.330 --> 00:53:25.840
Yeah.

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:29.230
How ready are American
archives for dealing

00:53:29.230 --> 00:53:33.086
with natural disasters
and other kinds of things?

00:53:33.086 --> 00:53:34.120
DAVID FERRIERO: [SIGHS]

00:53:34.120 --> 00:53:37.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:37.360 --> 00:53:39.830
SARA STEFANI: I'm also
groaning inwardly, actually.

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:42.070
Yeah.

00:53:42.070 --> 00:53:43.900
DAVID FERRIERO:
It's a tough one.

00:53:43.900 --> 00:53:47.275
How prepared are we?

00:53:47.275 --> 00:53:52.210
We have all kinds of
guidelines and stuff

00:53:52.210 --> 00:54:00.790
for natural disasters, but
when it hits, it's devastating.

00:54:00.790 --> 00:54:05.980
And we're so overtaxed in
terms of space for collections

00:54:05.980 --> 00:54:09.700
that we make bargains
with the devil

00:54:09.700 --> 00:54:14.390
about how we store stuff
and over-stuff places.

00:54:14.390 --> 00:54:19.777


00:54:19.777 --> 00:54:21.360
And we're talking
about the originals,

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:24.360
and that's why every
digitization effort

00:54:24.360 --> 00:54:28.140
is an opportunity to
preserve, to make sure

00:54:28.140 --> 00:54:31.500
that the content is
available in another format,

00:54:31.500 --> 00:54:34.800
in case there's some kind
of disaster like that.

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:37.140
SARA STEFANI: Yeah, and
also, I would add too

00:54:37.140 --> 00:54:41.670
that there's not an equity,
in terms of resources,

00:54:41.670 --> 00:54:43.470
to different archives.

00:54:43.470 --> 00:54:46.290
The National Archives,
I'm assuming,

00:54:46.290 --> 00:54:52.230
has state of the art
facilities and conditions.

00:54:52.230 --> 00:54:56.520
Here at IU we have an amazing
auxiliary library facility

00:54:56.520 --> 00:54:58.180
that has state of
the art conditions.

00:54:58.180 --> 00:55:02.490
But then you've got historical
societies and small archives

00:55:02.490 --> 00:55:07.290
in places where they
don't have that,

00:55:07.290 --> 00:55:11.790
and it's much more disastrous
when some kind of disaster

00:55:11.790 --> 00:55:13.290
hits, or a flood, or--

00:55:13.290 --> 00:55:14.400
DAVID FERRIERO: And
they're much more frequent,

00:55:14.400 --> 00:55:16.025
those disasters are
much more frequent.

00:55:16.025 --> 00:55:19.720
SARA STEFANI: Yeah and they're
happening much more frequently.

00:55:19.720 --> 00:55:23.010
So in a profession
that feels like we're

00:55:23.010 --> 00:55:27.570
frequently asked to do more
with less, in your career,

00:55:27.570 --> 00:55:31.470
how have you advocated
for appropriate staffing

00:55:31.470 --> 00:55:34.695
and resource levels to
support archival work?

00:55:34.695 --> 00:55:39.250


00:55:39.250 --> 00:55:44.350
DAVID FERRIERO: Ooh that's--
from the very beginning,

00:55:44.350 --> 00:55:46.750
archives aren't the
most important things

00:55:46.750 --> 00:55:53.140
in people's and funders'
minds, administration's minds.

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:54.430
Archives aren't sexy.

00:55:54.430 --> 00:55:57.430
Records aren't sexy.

00:55:57.430 --> 00:56:01.420
So there has to be
some kind of link

00:56:01.420 --> 00:56:08.290
to some initiative that
makes sense for the funding

00:56:08.290 --> 00:56:10.690
opportunity.

00:56:10.690 --> 00:56:14.770
Private foundations,
if you can demonstrate

00:56:14.770 --> 00:56:17.680
that you have something
that's of value

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:21.200
to a private foundation,
at least in my experience,

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:25.570
that sends a signal
to the administration

00:56:25.570 --> 00:56:29.020
funders that perhaps--

00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:33.760
if there's a requirement
for a matching gift--

00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:37.630
that this is an opportunity to
support something and create

00:56:37.630 --> 00:56:41.623
something great that
distinguishes the institution.

00:56:41.623 --> 00:56:43.040
We're always looking
for something

00:56:43.040 --> 00:56:48.620
that would impress the funders,
the administration, that

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:52.970
would raise the profile
of the institution.

00:56:52.970 --> 00:56:56.660
SARA STEFANI: Can I
ask a related question.

00:56:56.660 --> 00:57:00.110
So I'm assuming that most of
the funding of the National

00:57:00.110 --> 00:57:04.100
Archives comes from
Congress from appropriations

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:05.480
bills and et cetera.

00:57:05.480 --> 00:57:07.958
Does it cover all of the funding
for the National Archives?

00:57:07.958 --> 00:57:10.250
DAVID FERRIERO: No, we have
a private foundation, also,

00:57:10.250 --> 00:57:11.210
that raises money.

00:57:11.210 --> 00:57:14.240
And all the education
programs, exhibits,

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:17.900
are funded by the
private foundation.

00:57:17.900 --> 00:57:20.990
And the Presidential Libraries
have private foundations also.

00:57:20.990 --> 00:57:25.460
And they fund, depending
upon the library,

00:57:25.460 --> 00:57:27.380
various aspects of the work.

00:57:27.380 --> 00:57:28.250
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:57:28.250 --> 00:57:31.460
DAVID FERRIERO:
But the government

00:57:31.460 --> 00:57:35.000
work of maintaining
the records, that's

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:36.500
paid for by the government.

00:57:36.500 --> 00:57:38.090
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:57:38.090 --> 00:57:41.260
What is the process
for requesting access

00:57:41.260 --> 00:57:44.418
to restricted materials?

00:57:44.418 --> 00:57:46.960
DAVID FERRIERO: It depends on
what the restricted material is

00:57:46.960 --> 00:57:51.460
and what the requirements
are for access.

00:57:51.460 --> 00:57:54.850
You can file a FOIA request.

00:57:54.850 --> 00:58:02.320
And one of the ways to expedite
that FOIA request, if you're

00:58:02.320 --> 00:58:04.360
having trouble with
your FOIA request,

00:58:04.360 --> 00:58:08.530
there is a little
known organization

00:58:08.530 --> 00:58:11.290
unit within the
National Archives

00:58:11.290 --> 00:58:13.863
called the Office of Government
Information Services--

00:58:13.863 --> 00:58:15.530
SARA STEFANI: I have
to write that down.

00:58:15.530 --> 00:58:17.800
DAVID FERRIERO: --which
is the FOIA ombudsman,

00:58:17.800 --> 00:58:24.020
which serves to facilitate
access for the American public.

00:58:24.020 --> 00:58:28.300
So if you're having
trouble with the FBI

00:58:28.300 --> 00:58:31.930
and having your
request honored, you

00:58:31.930 --> 00:58:38.330
can work with my staff
and OTIS to expedite it.

00:58:38.330 --> 00:58:39.590
SARA STEFANI: OK.

00:58:39.590 --> 00:58:40.940
Can I ask a related question--

00:58:40.940 --> 00:58:44.210
DAVID FERRIERO: All of the FOIA
folks in all of the agencies,

00:58:44.210 --> 00:58:46.340
and I can tell you this
from personal experience,

00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:47.810
are overworked.

00:58:47.810 --> 00:58:50.580
There aren't enough people
handling FOIA requests.

00:58:50.580 --> 00:58:52.280
It's a huge problem

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:57.380
SARA STEFANI: Yeah, I recently
attended an online forum

00:58:57.380 --> 00:59:00.440
on the mandatory
declassification review

00:59:00.440 --> 00:59:05.840
process, and they said something
like, the vast majority of FOIA

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:11.450
requests come from only a
very small number of agencies

00:59:11.450 --> 00:59:12.590
or people, essentially.

00:59:12.590 --> 00:59:15.980
And that they make so many
requests that it clogs up

00:59:15.980 --> 00:59:18.680
the system a lot.

00:59:18.680 --> 00:59:20.300
And then a related
question to that

00:59:20.300 --> 00:59:23.900
too and along the lines
of what I just asked,

00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:27.772
is restricted materials but
also classified materials--

00:59:27.772 --> 00:59:28.730
DAVID FERRIERO: [GASPS]

00:59:28.730 --> 00:59:30.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:30.320 --> 00:59:35.160
SARA STEFANI: Because you
said, with sunshine week,

00:59:35.160 --> 00:59:37.410
the open government
celebration, you

00:59:37.410 --> 00:59:41.850
mentioned that the whole
point of the open government

00:59:41.850 --> 00:59:45.480
is transparency and avoiding
unnecessary secrecy.

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:49.680
But I think several people
think of classification

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:53.070
and classified documents as
that unnecessary secrecy.

00:59:53.070 --> 00:59:55.740
So who decides if
it's classified

00:59:55.740 --> 00:59:57.020
and how do you declassify it?

00:59:57.020 --> 00:59:58.800
DAVID FERRIERO:
It's a real issue.

00:59:58.800 --> 01:00:01.950
Another little known unit
within the National Archives

01:00:01.950 --> 01:00:04.290
is the Information
Security Oversight Office,

01:00:04.290 --> 01:00:06.270
which has responsibility
for overseeing

01:00:06.270 --> 01:00:09.360
all the classification
activity, monitoring it.

01:00:09.360 --> 01:00:15.210
And I can tell you that we
have a huge over classification

01:00:15.210 --> 01:00:19.260
problem within the government
in the executive branch.

01:00:19.260 --> 01:00:25.740
We now have in the neighborhood
of 2,500 original classifiers.

01:00:25.740 --> 01:00:28.230
These are folks who are
authorized to classify.

01:00:28.230 --> 01:00:32.880
This is down from about
9,500 when I started in 2009.

01:00:32.880 --> 01:00:35.610
So we've narrowed
the number of folks

01:00:35.610 --> 01:00:38.910
who have the responsibility
or have the ability.

01:00:38.910 --> 01:00:43.710
There are no standards
among those 2,500 people

01:00:43.710 --> 01:00:46.500
about what is top
secret and what

01:00:46.500 --> 01:00:49.320
might not be classified at all.

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:52.170
Unlike other countries
who have carved out what

01:00:52.170 --> 01:00:55.650
it means for each of the
classification areas.

01:00:55.650 --> 01:01:00.480
It's coupled with the fact
that the classification process

01:01:00.480 --> 01:01:01.410
is pretty tedious.

01:01:01.410 --> 01:01:05.010
It's line by line,
determining whether it really

01:01:05.010 --> 01:01:06.600
needs to be classified or not.

01:01:06.600 --> 01:01:09.570
And it's easier just to
classify the whole damn document

01:01:09.570 --> 01:01:13.170
than to do that line by line.

01:01:13.170 --> 01:01:18.220
And there was one more piece
of it, of the declassification.

01:01:18.220 --> 01:01:20.163
SARA STEFANI: Yeah,
I mean, that is also

01:01:20.163 --> 01:01:21.580
DAVID FERRIERO:
Regardless of what

01:01:21.580 --> 01:01:23.530
you may have read
in the press, it's

01:01:23.530 --> 01:01:26.810
about magic and
waving a magic wand.

01:01:26.810 --> 01:01:28.990
There is a
declassification process.

01:01:28.990 --> 01:01:32.600
Oh, I know what I was going to
say on the classification side.

01:01:32.600 --> 01:01:34.540
Especially in the
intelligence community,

01:01:34.540 --> 01:01:38.590
there are multiple agencies
that have equity in a document.

01:01:38.590 --> 01:01:42.220
So the classification
may have different levels

01:01:42.220 --> 01:01:45.440
of classification within
the same document.

01:01:45.440 --> 01:01:48.610
So that relates to
declassification also.

01:01:48.610 --> 01:01:52.930
So while the president does have
the authority to declassify,

01:01:52.930 --> 01:01:55.220
there is a process
that is followed,

01:01:55.220 --> 01:01:57.970
so that the agencies who did
the original classification

01:01:57.970 --> 01:01:59.192
are notified--

01:01:59.192 --> 01:02:00.400
SARA STEFANI: And can object.

01:02:00.400 --> 01:02:02.140
DAVID FERRIERO: --because
that's not the only copy.

01:02:02.140 --> 01:02:03.110
Oh, they can object.

01:02:03.110 --> 01:02:06.670
[LAUGHS] That's
not the only copy

01:02:06.670 --> 01:02:08.050
that sits in the White House.

01:02:08.050 --> 01:02:10.510
The agencies that did the
original classification,

01:02:10.510 --> 01:02:11.710
they have copies also.

01:02:11.710 --> 01:02:14.290
So it's very important
that the agencies

01:02:14.290 --> 01:02:17.750
be notified that that
has been declassified.

01:02:17.750 --> 01:02:20.330
SARA STEFANI: And if I
understand this correctly,

01:02:20.330 --> 01:02:25.520
one document can also
have the State Department

01:02:25.520 --> 01:02:26.270
has classified--

01:02:26.270 --> 01:02:27.140
DAVID FERRIERO:
Multiple equities.

01:02:27.140 --> 01:02:27.890
Yeah, exactly.

01:02:27.890 --> 01:02:31.370
SARA STEFANI: --the CIA
has classified part,

01:02:31.370 --> 01:02:33.750
the National Security Agency
has done a different--

01:02:33.750 --> 01:02:35.810
So and all of
those agencies have

01:02:35.810 --> 01:02:39.590
to declassify that particular
portion that they originally

01:02:39.590 --> 01:02:40.270
classified.

01:02:40.270 --> 01:02:40.820
DAVID FERRIERO: Yep.

01:02:40.820 --> 01:02:41.150
SARA STEFANI: Is that?

01:02:41.150 --> 01:02:41.690
DAVID FERRIERO: That's it.

01:02:41.690 --> 01:02:42.690
That's the way it works.

01:02:42.690 --> 01:02:44.030
SARA STEFANI: Yeah, no.

01:02:44.030 --> 01:02:44.930
Easy-peasy.

01:02:44.930 --> 01:02:46.070
All right.

01:02:46.070 --> 01:02:49.430
Your undergraduate degree
is in English literature.

01:02:49.430 --> 01:02:52.400
Can you speak to how that
degree or course of study

01:02:52.400 --> 01:02:55.310
influenced your career,
if it did at all,

01:02:55.310 --> 01:02:58.910
and/or the broader role of
education in the humanities

01:02:58.910 --> 01:03:01.700
in preparing people for
careers in information and/or

01:03:01.700 --> 01:03:04.790
public service.

01:03:04.790 --> 01:03:07.700
DAVID FERRIERO: I was
originally an education major.

01:03:07.700 --> 01:03:12.350
I always thought I was going
to teach when I first went

01:03:12.350 --> 01:03:14.030
to Northeastern University.

01:03:14.030 --> 01:03:20.970
And the education
courses were just so bad

01:03:20.970 --> 01:03:22.763
that I dropped out of school.

01:03:22.763 --> 01:03:23.430
SARA STEFANI: Oh

01:03:23.430 --> 01:03:24.305
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah.

01:03:24.305 --> 01:03:26.490
I Joined the Navy,
and when I came back,

01:03:26.490 --> 01:03:30.330
I was a liberal arts major and
had very different attitude

01:03:30.330 --> 01:03:31.590
toward higher education.

01:03:31.590 --> 01:03:35.700
And took courses that
were meaningful to me

01:03:35.700 --> 01:03:38.760
and a wide range across
history, and literature,

01:03:38.760 --> 01:03:41.640
and political science,
and psychology.

01:03:41.640 --> 01:03:45.540
And it was a well rounded
education which, I think,

01:03:45.540 --> 01:03:49.870
gave me an important basis
for higher education,

01:03:49.870 --> 01:03:52.530
but also thinking about careers.

01:03:52.530 --> 01:03:57.450
And at the same time I was
working in my co-op position

01:03:57.450 --> 01:04:01.230
as a junior library
assistant in the libraries

01:04:01.230 --> 01:04:05.100
at MIT, which exposed me to
all kinds of opportunities

01:04:05.100 --> 01:04:06.240
about library work.

01:04:06.240 --> 01:04:08.020
So it was the
combination of the two,

01:04:08.020 --> 01:04:11.287
I think, that put
me where I am today.

01:04:11.287 --> 01:04:12.370
SARA STEFANI: I like that.

01:04:12.370 --> 01:04:16.890
So you went from a junior
library position to working--

01:04:16.890 --> 01:04:18.640
DAVID FERRIERO: They
knew they had someone

01:04:18.640 --> 01:04:20.320
on the hook when I came.

01:04:20.320 --> 01:04:22.960
Because I just volunteered
to do anything.

01:04:22.960 --> 01:04:26.560
For those of you
who are old enough

01:04:26.560 --> 01:04:32.230
to remember filing in the shelf
list, I was allowed to file--

01:04:32.230 --> 01:04:34.600
me, a [INAUDIBLE]
student, was allowed

01:04:34.600 --> 01:04:38.950
to file in the
Southwest above the rod.

01:04:38.950 --> 01:04:42.520
Which means that someone,
a real professional,

01:04:42.520 --> 01:04:44.800
came behind me and checked
my work to pull the rod

01:04:44.800 --> 01:04:45.950
and drop the cart.

01:04:45.950 --> 01:04:47.980
So I wasn't doing
the filing, actually.

01:04:47.980 --> 01:04:49.120
SARA STEFANI: Oh, I see.

01:04:49.120 --> 01:04:50.050
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:50.050 --> 01:04:55.810
But you went from that to MIT,
and Duke, and the New York

01:04:55.810 --> 01:04:59.563
Public Library, and the
Archivist of the United States.

01:04:59.563 --> 01:05:00.730
DAVID FERRIERO: That's right

01:05:00.730 --> 01:05:01.150
SARA STEFANI: Yeah.

01:05:01.150 --> 01:05:01.983
DAVID FERRIERO: Hmm.

01:05:01.983 --> 01:05:03.250
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:03.250 --> 01:05:04.510
SARA STEFANI: Amazing.

01:05:04.510 --> 01:05:08.830
How do you view the new trend
of increased book banning

01:05:08.830 --> 01:05:12.310
and censorship, and
in what ways could it

01:05:12.310 --> 01:05:16.928
affect how our public
records are maintained?

01:05:16.928 --> 01:05:18.470
DAVID FERRIERO: It's
a good question.

01:05:18.470 --> 01:05:21.850
I think that it's just
a horrible situation.

01:05:21.850 --> 01:05:28.140
And I feel badly for
especially school librarians,

01:05:28.140 --> 01:05:31.680
who are the targets
of a lot of this--

01:05:31.680 --> 01:05:35.640
and some public
librarians, also.

01:05:35.640 --> 01:05:38.266
It's hard for me to imagine.

01:05:38.266 --> 01:05:39.630
No, I guess it's not hard.

01:05:39.630 --> 01:05:41.580
Anything, anything can happen.

01:05:41.580 --> 01:05:45.690
In terms of the
way records might

01:05:45.690 --> 01:05:50.760
be influenced, the way the
process works is that there

01:05:50.760 --> 01:05:54.210
are records managers
in each of the agencies

01:05:54.210 --> 01:05:57.360
who are responsible
for overseeing

01:05:57.360 --> 01:06:00.120
all the regulations about
creation and maintenance

01:06:00.120 --> 01:06:01.300
of records.

01:06:01.300 --> 01:06:07.320
So these are career
civil servants.

01:06:07.320 --> 01:06:12.520
They report, however,
to their agencies.

01:06:12.520 --> 01:06:14.400
It's something that
has bothered me,

01:06:14.400 --> 01:06:16.950
and in fact, I made
recommendations

01:06:16.950 --> 01:06:20.010
that all of the
records folks should

01:06:20.010 --> 01:06:21.330
be reporting to the archives.

01:06:21.330 --> 01:06:24.510


01:06:24.510 --> 01:06:28.480
Like the model that's used for
the Inspector General community

01:06:28.480 --> 01:06:30.250
within the federal government.

01:06:30.250 --> 01:06:33.040
They sit in the
agencies, but they

01:06:33.040 --> 01:06:38.650
report to a central
Inspector General Agency.

01:06:38.650 --> 01:06:43.240
There has been, and I can point
to several examples of bias

01:06:43.240 --> 01:06:47.860
in record keeping
in various agencies.

01:06:47.860 --> 01:06:51.100
Because of the
presidential appointment

01:06:51.100 --> 01:06:57.850
at the head of the Agency hiding
information or withholding

01:06:57.850 --> 01:06:58.850
information.

01:06:58.850 --> 01:07:01.760
And in some cases
changing information.

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:05.410
So those are things
that would be addressed.

01:07:05.410 --> 01:07:07.690
I think if that
records manager was

01:07:07.690 --> 01:07:09.520
more comfortable in
reporting it out.

01:07:09.520 --> 01:07:10.795
SARA STEFANI: Right, and
had some accountability.

01:07:10.795 --> 01:07:11.795
DAVID FERRIERO: Exactly.

01:07:11.795 --> 01:07:14.440
SARA STEFANI: And
somebody who could

01:07:14.440 --> 01:07:18.010
notice that and correct it.

01:07:18.010 --> 01:07:21.700
In terms of preservation,
while it is currently

01:07:21.700 --> 01:07:24.250
out of the capacity
for any authority

01:07:24.250 --> 01:07:26.740
to store absolutely
everything, do

01:07:26.740 --> 01:07:30.400
you think private corporations
have a responsibility

01:07:30.400 --> 01:07:33.322
to preserve?

01:07:33.322 --> 01:07:36.575
DAVID FERRIERO: Preserve their
own records, or preserve what?

01:07:36.575 --> 01:07:37.950
SARA STEFANI: So
I will continue.

01:07:37.950 --> 01:07:38.310
DAVID FERRIERO: Oh.

01:07:38.310 --> 01:07:38.850
[LAUGHS]

01:07:38.850 --> 01:07:41.790
SARA STEFANI: Do you think that
a website such as YouTube, one

01:07:41.790 --> 01:07:44.880
full of audio books, news
reports, historical footage,

01:07:44.880 --> 01:07:49.170
rare media, tutorials, cultural
touchstones, et cetera,

01:07:49.170 --> 01:07:52.950
has a responsibility to
maintain these archives,

01:07:52.950 --> 01:07:54.870
as they have inserted
themselves as such

01:07:54.870 --> 01:07:57.365
an important feature of the
modern world in other ways?

01:07:57.365 --> 01:07:58.990
DAVID FERRIERO: That's
a good question.

01:07:58.990 --> 01:08:00.008
SARA STEFANI: That
is a good one.

01:08:00.008 --> 01:08:00.883
DAVID FERRIERO: Yeah.

01:08:00.883 --> 01:08:03.430


01:08:03.430 --> 01:08:04.120
Sure.

01:08:04.120 --> 01:08:04.773
Yes.

01:08:04.773 --> 01:08:05.440
SARA STEFANI: OK

01:08:05.440 --> 01:08:06.395
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:06.395 --> 01:08:08.020
DAVID FERRIERO: Let's
make that happen.

01:08:08.020 --> 01:08:08.950
SARA STEFANI: OK.

01:08:08.950 --> 01:08:10.210
I like it.

01:08:10.210 --> 01:08:12.670
I mean, Yeah.

01:08:12.670 --> 01:08:17.319
I mean, I'm sort of struck,
and the details are fuzzy,

01:08:17.319 --> 01:08:21.910
but I know that there was an
incident not long ago where--

01:08:21.910 --> 01:08:24.910
I think it was
maybe in Ukraine--

01:08:24.910 --> 01:08:29.140
but somebody had posted
something and then immediately

01:08:29.140 --> 01:08:30.189
taken it down.

01:08:30.189 --> 01:08:32.859
But it was still in
the internet archives,

01:08:32.859 --> 01:08:37.300
and that was the only place that
had whatever this statement was

01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:40.359
or this document that was
put up online and immediately

01:08:40.359 --> 01:08:41.810
taken down.

01:08:41.810 --> 01:08:49.064
So I think this question of,
you have things on YouTube

01:08:49.064 --> 01:08:51.729
and whether they have
that responsibility

01:08:51.729 --> 01:08:53.689
as part of the record
is an interesting one.

01:08:53.689 --> 01:08:55.210
So.

01:08:55.210 --> 01:08:55.848
All right--

01:08:55.848 --> 01:08:57.640
DAVID FERRIERO: Can I
just share two things

01:08:57.640 --> 01:08:59.511
that I brought this
notebook to share.

01:08:59.511 --> 01:09:00.220
SARA STEFANI: Oh.

01:09:00.220 --> 01:09:02.303
DAVID FERRIERO: This thing
about access to records

01:09:02.303 --> 01:09:03.399
is something that--

01:09:03.399 --> 01:09:06.010
it wasn't until 1934
that legislation

01:09:06.010 --> 01:09:08.229
was signed to create
the National Archives,

01:09:08.229 --> 01:09:11.410
but the worry about
access to records

01:09:11.410 --> 01:09:14.020
goes way back to
the very beginning.

01:09:14.020 --> 01:09:19.450
And I got two letters from
Thomas Jefferson on this topic.

01:09:19.450 --> 01:09:22.870
In 1789, he wrote
that, "Whenever

01:09:22.870 --> 01:09:24.640
the people are
well informed, they

01:09:24.640 --> 01:09:26.470
can be trusted with
their own government.

01:09:26.470 --> 01:09:28.779
That whenever things
go so far wrong

01:09:28.779 --> 01:09:32.020
as to attract their notice,
they may be relied on

01:09:32.020 --> 01:09:33.790
to set them to rights."

01:09:33.790 --> 01:09:37.029
And then in 1791.

01:09:37.029 --> 01:09:38.140
That was 1789.

01:09:38.140 --> 01:09:42.430
In 1791 he said, "Time and
accident are committing

01:09:42.430 --> 01:09:45.910
daily havoc on the valuable
historical and state papers

01:09:45.910 --> 01:09:47.740
you have--

01:09:47.740 --> 01:09:48.460
I'm sorry.

01:09:48.460 --> 01:09:50.740
"Time and accident are
committing daily havoc

01:09:50.740 --> 01:09:53.710
on the originals deposited
in our public offices.

01:09:53.710 --> 01:09:57.460
The late war has done the work
of centuries in this business.

01:09:57.460 --> 01:09:59.240
The lost cannot be recovered.

01:09:59.240 --> 01:10:03.520
But let us save what remains,
not by vaults and locks which

01:10:03.520 --> 01:10:05.780
fence them from the
public eye and use

01:10:05.780 --> 01:10:08.190
and consigning them
to the waste of time.

01:10:08.190 --> 01:10:11.210
But by such multiplication
of copies as

01:10:11.210 --> 01:10:13.850
shall place them beyond
the reach of accident."

01:10:13.850 --> 01:10:15.890
Multiplication of copies.

01:10:15.890 --> 01:10:18.935
He is the grandfather
of my digitization work.

01:10:18.935 --> 01:10:20.110
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:20.110 --> 01:10:21.590
Multiplication of copies.

01:10:21.590 --> 01:10:24.410
And then Franklin Roosevelt,
when he was dedicating

01:10:24.410 --> 01:10:27.650
the Presidential Library said--

01:10:27.650 --> 01:10:30.350
he dedicated the
dedication of the library

01:10:30.350 --> 01:10:31.790
as an act of faith--

01:10:31.790 --> 01:10:33.837
"To bring together the
records of the past

01:10:33.837 --> 01:10:35.420
and to house them
into buildings where

01:10:35.420 --> 01:10:37.610
they will be preserved for
the use of men and women

01:10:37.610 --> 01:10:38.570
in the future.

01:10:38.570 --> 01:10:40.700
A nation must believe
in three things.

01:10:40.700 --> 01:10:42.110
It must believe in the past.

01:10:42.110 --> 01:10:44.010
It must believe in the future.

01:10:44.010 --> 01:10:47.730
It must, above all, believe in
the capacity of its own people.

01:10:47.730 --> 01:10:50.960
So to learn from the past
that they can gain in judgment

01:10:50.960 --> 01:10:53.010
in creating their own future."

01:10:53.010 --> 01:10:55.594
So that's what it's all about.

